</div>
<p>States awarded SSDI to about half the people in the sample. Although most of the denied applicants worked five years before applying, very few worked five years after, Schimmel Hyde and Wu found.</p>
<p>Employment rates fell most steeply for rejected applicants who came closest to qualifying: those deemed by their state&rsquo;s DDS to be too severely impaired to do their past work, but capable of switching to other work. Few did. (See graph.)</p>
<p><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1.png" alt="" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-248133" width="580" height="492" srcset="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1.png 580w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1-200x170.png 200w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1-400x339.png 400w" sizes="(max-width: 580px) 100vw, 580px"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-248133" width="580" height="492" data-sizes="(max-width: 580px) 100vw, 580px" data-srcset="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1.png 580w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1-200x170.png 200w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1-400x339.png 400w" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/8-9-18dif1.png" loading="lazy"></p>
<p>Over half of rejected applicants went on to get Social Security (disability or retirement) benefits before their full retirement age (65 or 66 for this sample) &mdash; either by successfully appealing their denial, filing a new disability application, or choosing<span> </span><a href="https://www.cbpp.org/blog/raising-social-securitys-retirement-age-cuts-benefits-for-all-retirees" class="jquery-once-1-processed">early retirement with reduced benefits</a>, the authors also found.</p>
<p>The new study adds to a body of research that has found dim labor-market and economic outcomes for denied SSDI applicants. A pioneering 1989 Government Accountability Office<span> </span><a href="https://www.gao.gov/assets/150/148345.pdf" class="jquery-once-1-processed">study</a><span> </span>documented that people denied SSDI benefits in the harsh<span> </span><a href="https://www.cbpp.org/blog/new-research-demographics-explains-most-of-disability-rolls-growth" class="jquery-once-1-processed">Reagan-era crackdown</a><span> </span>seldom worked again, suffered steep earnings declines if they did work, and had high poverty rates.</p>
<p>More recently, studies published in<span> </span><a href="https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.101.7.3308" class="jquery-once-1-processed">2011</a><span> </span>and<span> </span><a href="https://www.socialsecurity.gov/policy/docs/ssb/v75n4/v75n4p1.html" class="jquery-once-1-processed">2015</a>, which we summarized<span> </span><a href="https://www.cbpp.org/blog/van-de-water-work-expectations-for-disability-recipients-should-be-realistic-and-grounded-in" class="jquery-once-1-processed">here</a>, found large drops in work and earnings among rejected SSDI applicants. (Furthermore, those studies excluded many people who appealed their denial or who later reapplied, so those who remained were probably more able &mdash; and more likely to work &mdash; than the broader group that Schimmel Hyde and Wu studied.)</p>
<p>In short, many denied applicants suffer great economic harm from their disability but nevertheless don&rsquo;t qualify for benefits. Indeed, the United States has some of the most stringent eligibility criteria for disability benefits among advanced economies, and it<span> </span><a href="https://www.cbpp.org/blog/us-disability-benefits-modest-by-international-standards" class="jquery-once-1-processed">spends less</a><span> </span>than most. SSDI cushions but hardly eliminates the losses that breadwinners face when they suffer a severe impairment.</p>
